│  ## Abstract                                                                │
│                                                                             │
│  This study offers a critical examination of the complex relationship       │
│  between unidentified anomalous phenomena (UAP), often referred to as       │
│  unidentified flying objects (UFOs), and the conspiracy theories            │
│  surrounding extraterrestrials. The aim of this work is to analyze the      │
│  existing evidence, the mechanisms of formation of conspiracy theories in   │
│  this domain, and the psychological and social implications of these        │
│  beliefs. A careful review of findings from the All-domain Anomaly          │
│  Resolution Office (AARO) indicates no solid evidence supporting claims     │
│  that UAP sightings represent extraterrestrial technology, with most        │
│  sightings explained by misidentification of ordinary objects or phenomena  │
│  [1].                                                                       │
│                                                                             │
│  Despite the absence of definitive scientific evidence, conspiracy          │
│  theories regarding extraterrestrials continue to persist and flourish.     │
│  This work explores these theories as modern myths that serve deep          │
│  psychological and social needs, such as the need to explain the            │
│  complexity of the universe and the meaning of human existence [2]. We      │
│  analyze the role of cognitive biases, intuitive thinking patterns, and     │
│  distrust in official institutions in the dissemination of these beliefs.   │
│  Furthermore, we examine the rhetorical tactics employed by conspiracy      │
│  theories, such as reliance on blurred photographs and unverified           │
│  eyewitness testimonies [2]. The discussion will also include the           │
│  connection between conspiracy theories and feelings of insecurity,         │
│  postmodern anxieties, and correlations with paranoia and trust [5, 6, 7].  │
│  The study's conclusions will highlight the discrepancy between empirical   │
│  data and conspiracy narratives, pointing to the need for further research  │
│  into mechanisms of meaning-making and coping with uncertainty in modern    │
│  society.                                                                   │
│                                                                             │
